{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502958","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502958"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:52:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:52:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1917"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1917","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1917"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.51,0.19,0.17,0.06,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1917"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56377"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1917","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1917"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1917"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41925"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"401"},{"type":"tags","id":"1074"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"29"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30"},{"type":"contributions","id":"151"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40344"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56377","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/56377"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 57-year-old woman presents to the outpatient Neurology clinic with an 18-month history of shaking in her right hand. The shaking worsens when she tries to use her hand and is not present at rest. Her handwriting has become \u0022very shaky\u0022 and she has great difficulty filling in forms. She has a medical history of eosinophilic asthma with recurrent hospital admissions. Her regular medication is budesonide/formoterol inhaler as both a preventer and reliever. She has no known drug allergies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination reveals no tremor at rest. However, when she holds her hand up, there is a fine tremor that is augmented by clenching her fist. The remainder of the neurological examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Propranolol","Primidone","Levodopa/carbidopa","Selegiline","Benzhexol"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms and signs consistent with essential tremor, which typically manifests as a bilateral postural tremor predominantly affecting the hands and worsening with voluntary movement. The two first-line treatments for essential tremor are nonselective beta-blockers (such as \u003Cstrong\u003Epropranolol\u003C/strong\u003E) and anticonvulsants (such as \u003Cstrong\u003Eprimidone\u003C/strong\u003E).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, \u003Cstrong\u003Eprimidone\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial management. While propranolol is often considered first-line, it is contraindicated in this patient due to her history of asthma. Beta-blockers can cause bronchospasm in asthmatic patients, potentially exacerbating their condition. Primidone, an anticonvulsant, does not carry this risk and is equally effective in managing essential tremor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPropranolol\u003C/strong\u003E, although effective for essential tremor, is contraindicated in this patient due to her asthma. Beta-blockers can cause bronchospasm and worsen asthma symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELevodopa/carbidopa\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily used in the treatment of Parkinson\u0027s disease. It is not indicated for essential tremor. Parkinsonian tremor is typically a resting tremor that improves with movement, unlike the postural and action tremor seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESelegiline\u003C/strong\u003E is a monoamine oxidase B inhibitor used in the treatment of Parkinson\u0027s disease. It is not effective for essential tremor and would not be an appropriate choice in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBenzhexol\u003C/strong\u003E (also known as trihexyphenidyl) is an anticholinergic medication sometimes used in Parkinson\u0027s disease to manage tremor. However, it is not indicated for essential tremor and can have significant side effects, especially in older adults.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn managing essential tremor, it\u0027s important to consider the patient\u0027s overall health and potential contraindications. While beta-blockers are often first-line, alternatives like primidone are equally effective and may be more appropriate in certain patient populations, such as those with asthma or other contraindications to beta-blockers.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Essential tremor typically presents as a bilateral postural tremor affecting the hands, worsening with voluntary movement and improving at rest.","Primidone is a first-line treatment for essential tremor, especially in patients with contraindications to beta-blockers.","Beta-blockers like propranolol are contraindicated in patients with asthma due to the risk of bronchospasm."],"references":["Pal PK. Guidelines for management of essential tremor. Ann Indian Acad Neurol. 2011;14(1):S25-8. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3152172/","Farzam K, Jan A. Beta Blockers. In: StatPearls [online]. 2023. Accessed 2020. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK532906/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41925"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1917"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41925","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41925"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-20T08:47:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-12T01:11:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1917"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56377"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"ta